Description

The data is from: Box Office Mojo, IMDb (rating, directors, actors,awards), Rotten Tomatoes (rating, # of reviews).

  • Continuous
    • Financials:Worldwide, Domestic, Overseas, Openingweekend, theater, weeks (highly correlated)
    • Budget
    • Runtime
    • Rating related:IMDB rating, rotten tomatoes rating, # of reviews
  • Category
    • Studio
    • MPAA
    • Year
    • Release_Date > Period
    • Genre (Genre 1&2)
  • Other
    • Director
    • Actor12 #Part I data import and cleaning ##1.read scrapped data (from Box office Mojo and IMDb) Original data could be found here: http://www.boxofficemojo.com http://www.imdb.com All text data files (.txt) used are listed :undo_data, people (IMDb director and stars),rt (rotten tomatoes reviewing and total number of reviews),inflation (adjusted movie price),IMDb (awards: times of winning an award and times of nomitation.)
data =read.delim("/Users/mac/Dropbox/EDSP/undo_data.txt", header =T,sep="\t")
require(reshape2)
## Loading required package: reshape2
df<-data.frame(matrix(ncol = 20, nrow =633))  
colnames(df)<-c('number','rank','title','studio','worldwide','domestic','overseas',
                'year','release_date','release_year','genre','runtime','mpaa','bugdet',
                'opening_weekend','duration','director','actors','theater','rating')
for (i in 1:633){
  df[i,]<-colsplit(data[i,], ",",c('number','rank','title','studio','worldwide','domestic','overseas',
                               'year','release_date','release_year','genre','runtime','mpaa','bugdet',
                               'opening_weekend','duration','director','actors','theater','rating'))
}

2.data cleaning

2.1 delete variables: year,directors,actors(messy) 2.2 split genre 2.3 transfer opening_weekend data to numerical million level,digit=1 and fixxed ow data.

df$year <- NULL
df$actors<- NULL
df$director<-NULL
df$genre <- gsub('Action / Adventure', 'AA', df$genre)
library(stringr)
genrematrix<-str_split_fixed(df$genre, " ", 2)
df$genre1<-genrematrix[,1]
df$genre2<-genrematrix[,2]
df$genre2 <- gsub('/ ', '', df$genre2)
df$ow<-round(as.numeric(df$opening_weekend)/1000000,digits=1)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
df$opening_weekend<- NULL
df$ow[df$ow>=250]<-NA

2.4 transfer date data + transfer release date + transfer runtime to mins + seperate duration (generate weeks as the number of week (duration))

date<-as.POSIXlt(strptime(df$release_date,"%B %d"))
run <- gsub('min.', '', gsub('hrs. ', ',', df$runtime))
runmatrix<-str_split_fixed(run, ",", 2)
df$runt<-as.numeric(runmatrix[,1])*60+as.numeric(runmatrix[,2])
df$runtime <- NULL
df$duration <- gsub(' / ', ',', df$duration)
duramatrix<-str_split_fixed(df$duration, ",", 2)
df$duration<- NULL
df$weeks<-as.numeric(gsub('weeks','',duramatrix[,2]))
df$ow[is.na(df$weeks)]<-NA

3. create variables

3.1 Period * summer season(ss):late May- late Aug (5-20,8-31) * holiday season(hs):late Nov- Jan (11-20,1-7) * other: (ns)

df$period<-as.POSIXct(strptime(df$release_date,"%B %d"))
df$per<- ifelse((df$period>=as.POSIXct(as.character("2016-05-20")))&
                     (df$period<=as.POSIXct(as.character("2016-08-31"))),"ss",df$period)
df$per<- ifelse((df$period>=as.POSIXct(as.character("2016-11-20")))|
                     (df$period<=as.POSIXct(as.character("2016-01-07"))),"hs",df$per)
df$per<- ifelse((df$per!="ss")&(df$per!= "hs"),"ns",df$per)
df$period<-NULL

3.2 Super hero movies Create a label to distinguish super hero movie or not ($hero) 1. BV + marvels avengers + iron man + guardians of the galaxy + the incredibles + captain america + big hero + ant-man + unbreakable + skyhigh

  1. WB
  • the dark knight
  • man of steel

  • greenlaten
  • catwoman
  1. Sony
  • spiderman
  • hancock
  1. Fox
  • deadpool
  • x_men
  • fantastic four
  1. Par.
  • ironman
df$title1<-df$title
df$title1<-gsub("Episode III","",df$title1)
df$title1<-gsub("Episode II","",df$title1)
df$title1<-gsub("Episode I","",df$title1)
df$title1<-gsub("-","",df$title1)
df$title1<-gsub(",","",df$title1)
df$title1<-tolower(df$title1)
df$title1<-gsub(" ","",df$title1)
b1<-union(grep(("avengers"),df$title1),grep("ironman",df$title1))
b2<-union(grep("guardiansofthegalaxy",df$title1),grep("theincredibles",df$title1))
b3<-union(grep("captainamerica",df$title1),grep("bighero",df$title1))
b4<-union(b3,grep("antman",df$title1))
b5<-union(b1,b2)
bv<-union(b4,b5)
#WB=2
w1<-union(grep("thedarkknight",df$title1),grep("manofsteel",df$title1))
w2<-union(grep("batman",df$title1),grep("superman",df$title1))
wb<-union(w1,w2)
#Sony=3
sony<-union(grep("spiderman",df$title1),grep("hancock",df$title1))
#Fox=4
fox<-union(grep("xmen",df$title1),grep("fantasticfour",df$title1))
#Par.=5
par<-grep("ironman",df$title1)
#create superhero variable
df$sh<-0
df$sh[bv]<-1
df$sh[wb]<-2
df$sh[sony]<-3
df$sh[fox]<-4
df$sh[par]<-5

3.6 Adjusted for inflation (modeling I)

inf<-read.csv("/Users/mac/Dropbox/EDSP/inflation.csv",header =T)
inf$avg<-gsub("\\$","",inf$Avg..Price)
inf$Avg..Price<-NULL
df$price<-0
for (i in 2:nrow(inf)){
  df$price[grep(inf$Year[i],df$release_year)]<-inf$avg[i]    
}
df$adjusted<-8.7*df$domestic/as.numeric(df$price)
df$adow<-round(8.7*df$ow/as.numeric(df$price),2)
df$adbudget<-round(8.7*df$budget/as.numeric(df$price),2)
df$adjusted<-round(df$adjusted,2)

perbar=function(xx){
q=ggplot(data=data.frame(xx),aes(x=xx))+
geom_bar(aes(y = (..count..)),fill="orange")+
geom_text(aes(y = (..count..),label =   ifelse((..count..)==0,"",scales::percent((..count..)/sum(..count..)))), stat="bin",colour="darkgreen") 
q
}

For more than 600 movies ranked by global box office revenues over 7 decades, most of them are released after year 2000. There might be several reasons: 1. There is a price inflation over time 2. Movie industry keeps booming, watching movie has become one important entertainment in peoples daily life. 3.There is a raid overseas movie markets expansion since 21st century. In order to prove 1 and 2, we use the adjusted data which eliminates price inflation and only focuses on domestic market to see the bar color changes. It seems that hypothesis 2 holds. In order to have a general understanding of the overseas market effect, some visulizations are made: (For the barplot, I just use movies released from year 1980) B. Overseas markets expands after year 1987
